In Java, you can handle exceptions using try-catch blocks. The try block contains the code that might throw an exception, and the catch block contains the code that will handle the exception. Here's an example:

```
try {
    // Code that might throw an exception
} catch (ExceptionType e) {
    // Code to handle the exception
}
```

You can also have multiple catch blocks to handle different types of exceptions. Additionally, you can use the finally block to execute code regardless of whether an exception was thrown or not.

```
try {
    // Code that might throw an exception
} catch (ExceptionType1 e) {
    // Code to handle ExceptionType1
} catch (ExceptionType2 e) {
    // Code to handle ExceptionType2
} finally {
    // Code to execute regardless of whether an exception was thrown or not
}
```

It's also important to remember to handle checked exceptions properly. Checked exceptions are exceptions that are checked at compile-time, meaning that you must either handle them or declare them in the method signature. Unchecked exceptions, on the other hand, are not checked at compile-time and are typically used for programming errors.

